1
00:00:03,439 --> 00:00:05,430
ljust read about an experiment...

2
00:00:05,639 --> 00:00:08,517
...to see if you can make two people
fall in love in hours.

3
00:00:08,719 --> 00:00:09,993
That doesn't sound right.

4
00:00:10,199 --> 00:00:14,795
My research has shown that it takes
three to five years of shameless begging.

5
00:00:15,199 --> 00:00:17,633
Honey, neither of us comes off good
in that story.

6
00:00:18,079 --> 00:00:20,991
Yeah, I saw that article you're talking about.

7
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:23,839
The participants ask each other
a series of questions...

8
00:00:24,039 --> 00:00:25,552
...designed to promote intimacy.

9
00:00:25,759 --> 00:00:28,671
And finish it off by staring
into each other's eyes for four minutes.

10
00:00:28,839 --> 00:00:32,036
Oh, that's nonsense.
I proclaimed my love for you...

11
00:00:32,240 --> 00:00:36,438
...and the last time I looked into your eyes
you thought you had conjunctivitis.

12
00:00:36,959 --> 00:00:40,156
Other than the fact that I had it,
that was a magical night.

13
00:00:41,600 --> 00:00:44,068
Raj, would you try an experiment
like that with Emily?

14
00:00:44,280 --> 00:00:46,111
I don't need science to win her heart.

15
00:00:46,319 --> 00:00:48,958
l have my family's wealth for that.

16
00:00:49,159 --> 00:00:52,356
I'm telling you, you can't create love
in a few hours. Right?

17
00:00:52,559 --> 00:00:55,631
Careful. You're poking
at the whole foundation of The Bachelor.

18
00:00:57,080 --> 00:00:59,913
Yeah, well, we don't have to debate this.
We're scientists.

19
00:01:00,120 --> 00:01:01,758
We can conduct our own research.

20
00:01:01,959 --> 00:01:06,430
-I propose we imprison two street people--
-No.

21
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:10,240
-You didn't even let me finish.
-Forget it.

22
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:13,119
Oh! So you can experiment
on all the apes you want...

23
00:01:13,320 --> 00:01:16,392
...but I wanna manipulate the emotions
of two captive human beings...

24
00:01:16,559 --> 00:01:18,231
...suddenly I'm the monster.

25
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:21,754
Why don't you just do the test?

26
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:24,758
In the interest of science, I'd be willing to.

27
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:27,599
You're okay with an experiment
where you answer questions...

28
00:01:27,800 --> 00:01:29,552
...about your innermost feelings?

29
00:01:30,120 --> 00:01:32,634
-Yes.
-Please, can I do it with him? Please?

30
00:01:34,600 --> 00:01:37,478
I've been listening to Sheldon's feelings
on things for 10 years.

31
00:01:37,640 --> 00:01:38,755
Tag, you're it.

32
00:01:39,240 --> 00:01:42,869
-Yeah, but what if the experiment works?
-l'm not gonna fall in love with Sheldon.

33
00:01:43,039 --> 00:01:44,028
AMY:
That's what I said.

34
00:01:44,240 --> 00:01:47,550
Before I knew it,
he pontificated his way right into my heart.

35
00:01:48,039 --> 00:01:51,918
Uh, fun fact: "Pontificate"
comes from the Latin word "pontifex"...

36
00:01:52,119 --> 00:01:55,031
...which means bridge builder or pope.

37
00:01:57,280 --> 00:01:58,554
In love yet?

38
00:02:24,559 --> 00:02:26,311
Just out of curiosity, Penny...

39
00:02:26,520 --> 00:02:29,512
...if this experiment
does make us fall in love...

40
00:02:29,720 --> 00:02:34,589
...would you drive me to Lake Geneva,
Wisconsin, for Gary Con?

41
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:39,554
It's the only convention celebrating
the life and work of Gary Gygax...

42
00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:42,433
...the cocreator of Dungeons & Dragons.

43
00:02:43,639 --> 00:02:46,073
You know what?
I can honestly say if we fall in love...

44
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:50,631
...not only will I drive you there, I will
buy you all the dragon T-shirts you want.

45
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:54,035
Okay, babe, let's do this.

46
00:02:57,279 --> 00:03:00,794
You guys are really being calm
about Penny and Sheldon doing this thing.

47
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,197
-Uh, if it were me, I'd be a little nervous.
-Why?

48
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:07,915
Even if the study's nonsense,
I don't believe in tempting fate.

49
00:03:08,120 --> 00:03:12,398
Same reason I wouldn't use a Ouija board
or pick a fight with an Asian guy.

50
00:03:12,600 --> 00:03:15,353
Probably doesn't know karate,
but why risk it?

51
00:03:16,760 --> 00:03:17,749
I think we're safe.

52
00:03:17,959 --> 00:03:23,079
That's what the bullies at Bruce Lee's
high school thought, and then, bam, karate.

53
00:03:24,040 --> 00:03:26,600
Are we just gonna sit here
while they do the experiment?

54
00:03:26,800 --> 00:03:29,553
-The two of us could do it.
-Yeah, sure, that might be fun.

55
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:33,150
-What's the first question?
-Hang on. Okay.

56
00:03:34,239 --> 00:03:39,916
"Given the choice of anyone in the world,
whom would you want as a dinner guest?"

57
00:03:40,120 --> 00:03:41,109
Hmm.

58
00:03:41,400 --> 00:03:43,789
I can honestly say Penny.

59
00:03:44,120 --> 00:03:45,109
Awww.

60
00:03:45,279 --> 00:03:48,749
Then I choose ajanitor,
because I'm about to throw up.

61
00:03:50,800 --> 00:03:53,189
I'm in love. Let's do something else.

62
00:03:54,840 --> 00:03:56,319
Ooh, uh, Emily gets off work soon.

63
00:03:56,519 --> 00:03:58,157
-Why don't the four of us go out?
-Okay.

64
00:03:58,319 --> 00:04:00,628
-Sounds good.
-Should we call Howard and Bernadette?

65
00:04:00,840 --> 00:04:03,673
I don't know when their plane gets in.
Let me shoot them a text.

66
00:04:03,880 --> 00:04:05,996
Did he say anything about the funeral?

67
00:04:06,200 --> 00:04:08,589
Not much,
but he seemed to be in a pretty good place.

68
00:04:08,799 --> 00:04:12,872
Are you kidding me?
You lost my mother's ashes?

69
00:04:13,359 --> 00:04:16,476
No, I'm just saying
that sometimes bags are misrouted.

70
00:04:16,680 --> 00:04:20,070
All right, fine. Where did you misroute
the only woman who ever loved me?

71
00:04:20,280 --> 00:04:23,078
The first wo-- First. I meant first.

72
00:04:24,439 --> 00:04:27,351
ljust need some information.
Uh, what's the flight number?

73
00:04:27,560 --> 00:04:28,595
Eight-sixteen.

74
00:04:29,079 --> 00:04:32,435
-I really did mean first.
-Just drop it.

75
00:04:32,919 --> 00:04:34,193
And can you describe the bag?

76
00:04:34,359 --> 00:04:37,351
Um, it's, uh, black.
There's a red ribbon tied to the handle--

77
00:04:37,560 --> 00:04:40,518
The world's greatest mom
is in the shoe compartment.

78
00:04:41,960 --> 00:04:44,269
-Are you ready to begin?
-Yeah, be right there.

79
00:04:44,479 --> 00:04:46,674
-I assume you don't want wine.
-Correct.

80
00:04:46,879 --> 00:04:50,189
You're not supposed to drink alcohol
when operating heavy machinery.

81
00:04:50,400 --> 00:04:51,958
What heavy machinery?

82
00:04:55,959 --> 00:04:57,153
Let's just start.

83
00:04:57,359 --> 00:05:01,068
Well, as a Texas gentleman,
I'm inclined to say ladies first.

84
00:05:01,280 --> 00:05:04,238
Although I'm concerned
that level of politeness and charm...

85
00:05:04,440 --> 00:05:07,398
...might make you fall in love with me
before the test even begins.

86
00:05:07,599 --> 00:05:10,875
Perhaps we should flip a coin.
Or if you're familiar with the rules...

87
00:05:11,079 --> 00:05:13,547
-...of "Rock, Paper, Scissors, Lizard--"
-Question one.

88
00:05:14,720 --> 00:05:18,554
"Given the choice of anyone in the world,
whom would you want as a dinner guest?"

89
00:05:18,759 --> 00:05:19,874
Hmm.

90
00:05:20,199 --> 00:05:22,667
-Living or dead?
-It just says "anyone in the world."

91
00:05:22,879 --> 00:05:25,154
-I guess that means living.
-Eh, it's just as well.

92
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:28,716
As much as I'd love to meet Euclid,
inventor of the geometric proof...

93
00:05:28,919 --> 00:05:32,434
...he probably wore sandals,
and I cannot look at toes during dinner.

94
00:05:34,280 --> 00:05:35,679
Oh, I know.

95
00:05:35,879 --> 00:05:39,554
The person I'd most like
to have dinner with is myself.

96
00:05:41,079 --> 00:05:43,991
You sure that's your choice?
Because I've had that dinner.

97
00:05:44,479 --> 00:05:45,468
Well, I haven't.

98
00:05:45,680 --> 00:05:49,753
And while they say never meet your heroes,
I just don't see howl could disappoint.

99
00:05:49,959 --> 00:05:52,519
-Who would you choose?
-Robert Downey Jr.

100
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:54,272
Ye- Oh....

101
00:05:54,679 --> 00:05:57,239
I didn't think of Iron Man.

102
00:05:58,639 --> 00:06:02,518
Maybe after myself and l have dinner,
we can meet you two for dessert.

103
00:06:05,440 --> 00:06:06,429
[SIGHS]

104
00:06:06,599 --> 00:06:10,069
-So, what do you guys wanna do?
-We're the ones tagging along. You pick.

105
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:11,998
Ooh, have you ever been
to an escape room?

106
00:06:12,199 --> 00:06:14,838
-Uh-uh, what's that?
-Um, it's kind of like interactive theater.

107
00:06:15,040 --> 00:06:17,998
You have to solve puzzles
in a certain amount of time to get out.

108
00:06:18,200 --> 00:06:20,794
There's one downtown where they
trap you in a room with a zombie.

109
00:06:20,959 --> 00:06:22,438
LEONARD: Hmm.
RAJESH: Ooh.

110
00:06:22,839 --> 00:06:25,672
So kind of like what's happening
with Penny right now.

111
00:06:28,959 --> 00:06:32,190
"What would constitute a perfect day
for you?"

112
00:06:33,039 --> 00:06:37,191
Uh, well, I'd probably sleep in,
do a little yoga...

113
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:41,992
...then lie on the beach
while cute cabana boys brought me drinks...

114
00:06:42,200 --> 00:06:45,670
...and probably get a massage and then
cap off the night with some dancing.

115
00:06:46,119 --> 00:06:47,108
That's it?

116
00:06:47,319 --> 00:06:49,514
-Yeah, why?
-You didn't mention Leonard.

117
00:06:51,799 --> 00:06:53,869
He's there.

118
00:06:55,120 --> 00:06:56,269
I don't think so.

119
00:06:56,480 --> 00:07:00,837
Leonard can't stand yoga,
the beach, massages or dancing.

120
00:07:01,040 --> 00:07:04,032
Yeah, well, he brought a book, okay?
What's yours?

121
00:07:05,639 --> 00:07:07,197
Uh, I wake up.

122
00:07:07,399 --> 00:07:11,358
I enjoy some French toast
with butter and syrup.

123
00:07:11,559 --> 00:07:12,878
Uh, then a wormhole opens...

124
00:07:13,639 --> 00:07:17,348
...and whisks me millions of years
into the future...

125
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:22,236
...where my towering intellect is used
to save the last remnants of mankind...

126
00:07:22,439 --> 00:07:25,237
...from a predatory alien race.

127
00:07:26,399 --> 00:07:28,629
Interesting you didn't mention Amy.

128
00:07:29,919 --> 00:07:33,116
Who do you think made the French toast
with butter and syrup?

129
00:07:34,559 --> 00:07:38,029
You're about to enter the lab
of the late Dr. David Saltzberg.

130
00:07:38,239 --> 00:07:40,958
While conducting studies
on slowing the aging process...

131
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:44,197
...there was a catastrophic accident,
and he died.

132
00:07:45,919 --> 00:07:47,637
Or did he?

133
00:07:48,959 --> 00:07:51,348
-Ladies.
-Are you being polite or scared?

134
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:54,393
Yep.

135
00:07:57,159 --> 00:07:59,354
[ALL OOH-ING AND AAH-ING]

136
00:08:00,560 --> 00:08:02,278
[DOOR SLAMS AND LOCKS]

137
00:08:03,359 --> 00:08:05,827
-This is cool.
-So how do we start?

138
00:08:06,040 --> 00:08:08,031
We look for the clues
hidden around the room.

139
00:08:08,239 --> 00:08:10,469
Uh, wasn't there supposed to be a zombie?

140
00:08:10,639 --> 00:08:12,755
[SHRIEKS THEN WHIMPERS]

141
00:08:14,160 --> 00:08:17,835
Okay, let's hope one of the clues
is written on a pair of clean underwear.

142
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:18,955
[ZOMBIE MOANS]

143
00:08:20,399 --> 00:08:21,627
Mr. and Mrs. Wolowitz?

144
00:08:21,839 --> 00:08:24,672
As far as I can tell,
your bag arrived in Los Angeles.

145
00:08:24,880 --> 00:08:26,836
-So where is it?
-I don't know.

146
00:08:27,040 --> 00:08:29,759
Perhaps somebody took it off the carousel
by mistake.

147
00:08:30,599 --> 00:08:32,829
So some stranger has my mom?

148
00:08:33,279 --> 00:08:34,678
Is that what you're telling me?

149
00:08:34,879 --> 00:08:38,155
My poor mother can be anywhere
in Los Angeles right now?

150
00:08:38,360 --> 00:08:40,669
lwish l was telling you that...

151
00:08:41,519 --> 00:08:45,876
...um, but the passenger could have gotten
on an international flight.

152
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:49,471
Oh, okay, great,
so your entire job is to find lost luggage...

153
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:53,992
...and you've narrowed down the location
of my mother to the planet Earth.

154
00:08:54,199 --> 00:08:55,348
I'm sorry.

155
00:08:55,560 --> 00:08:59,838
Would 500 frequent-flyer miles help?
That could get you to Sacramento.

156
00:09:02,879 --> 00:09:04,790
"If you could wake up tomorrow...

157
00:09:04,999 --> 00:09:09,390
...having gained any one quality or ability,
what would it be?"

158
00:09:09,920 --> 00:09:11,638
Well, not to steal from the Bible...

159
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:15,196
...but turning water into wine
sounds pretty good.

160
00:09:18,199 --> 00:09:21,077
I don't think you're taking this seriously.

161
00:09:21,280 --> 00:09:23,748
Come on.
I'm just having some fun with you.

162
00:09:23,960 --> 00:09:27,873
I believe what you're doing is using humor
to avoid vulnerability.

163
00:09:29,279 --> 00:09:31,076
Fine.

164
00:09:31,439 --> 00:09:33,236
Honestly?

165
00:09:33,439 --> 00:09:35,350
lfl could have one quality...

166
00:09:35,560 --> 00:09:38,791
...I wish I could be as smart as you guys.

167
00:09:38,999 --> 00:09:40,955
Ha! Keep dreaming.

168
00:09:42,439 --> 00:09:44,589
-Sheldon.
-Oh, I'm sorry.

169
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:46,313
That was me having fun with you.

170
00:09:47,240 --> 00:09:52,872
Look, you may not be
as academically inclined as are we--

171
00:09:53,079 --> 00:09:55,149
Yes, that's how you say it.

172
00:09:58,040 --> 00:10:00,600
--but you possess an intelligence I envy...

173
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:02,995
-Hmm?
-...which leads me to my answer:

174
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:07,079
I would choose the ability
to read people's minds.

175
00:10:07,720 --> 00:10:10,632
Well, I can't read people's minds.

176
00:10:10,840 --> 00:10:13,035
Actually, that's not true.
I can read men's minds.

177
00:10:13,199 --> 00:10:15,155
But only because it's usually the one thing.

178
00:10:16,839 --> 00:10:19,478
When are we going to get robot eyes?

179
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:23,040
You're all alike.

180
00:10:23,240 --> 00:10:25,310
Well, whatl meant was...

181
00:10:25,999 --> 00:10:29,230
...I often misinterpret how others are feeling.

182
00:10:29,439 --> 00:10:33,876
Like, I can't always tell if someone
is onlyjoking or laughing at me.

183
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:37,868
You know, like, if they're mad at
something I've done orjust in a bad mood.

184
00:10:38,080 --> 00:10:40,036
It's incredibly stressful.

185
00:10:40,519 --> 00:10:43,670
-Really? You always seem so confident.
-Well, I'm not.

186
00:10:43,879 --> 00:10:48,794
And ifl could read people's minds,
life would be so much simpler.

187
00:10:49,920 --> 00:10:54,198
Well, now I wish I had the ability
to make that stuff easier for you.

188
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:57,992
-Well,thank you.
-Mmm.

189
00:11:01,599 --> 00:11:05,387
Wow. I just felt this wave
of affection for you.

190
00:11:07,400 --> 00:11:09,595
You sure it's not too much Biblejuice?

191
00:11:12,480 --> 00:11:14,072
And the wave is gone.

192
00:11:18,400 --> 00:11:19,469
Brains.

193
00:11:19,680 --> 00:11:23,832
-Keep it down. We're working here.
-Okay, we've got the cipher decoded.

194
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:25,393
How's it going with the globe?

195
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:29,479
-We used the coordinates to locate cities.
-l'm putting the city names in the grid.

196
00:11:29,639 --> 00:11:33,427
-That'll give us the code to the safe.
-Solve puzzle too fast. Slow down.

197
00:11:34,520 --> 00:11:39,594
-Yep, got the code.
-Just saying, no refund for finish early.

198
00:11:43,919 --> 00:11:45,318
Sure you don't wanna go home?

199
00:11:45,520 --> 00:11:47,795
When the bag's returned,
they'll deliver it to us.

200
00:11:47,999 --> 00:11:50,672
No. I'm not leaving without her.

201
00:11:50,879 --> 00:11:53,439
You're right. We'll wait.

202
00:11:56,599 --> 00:11:59,750
-I could have driven her.
-What?

203
00:12:00,199 --> 00:12:02,793
The day she left for Florida...

204
00:12:03,439 --> 00:12:06,237
...she asked me to drive her to the airport.

205
00:12:08,240 --> 00:12:09,798
l was too busy...

206
00:12:10,680 --> 00:12:14,798
...and I made her take a cab.

207
00:12:16,680 --> 00:12:19,148
l was too busy.

208
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:21,711
There's no way you could have known.

209
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:25,349
Be right back.

210
00:12:28,560 --> 00:12:31,279
-Excuse me.
-Yes?

211
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:34,918
You better find my husband's mother...

212
00:12:35,120 --> 00:12:39,113
...because one way or another, we're walking
out of this airport with a dead woman.

213
00:12:42,839 --> 00:12:43,828
[ZOMBIE MOANING]

214
00:12:44,279 --> 00:12:45,678
Which book are we looking for?

215
00:12:45,879 --> 00:12:48,837
-Uh, Origin of Species.
-Here it is.

216
00:12:49,479 --> 00:12:51,231
-There's a black light.
-Oh, hang on.

217
00:12:51,480 --> 00:12:52,674
[ZOMBIE MOANS]

218
00:12:54,839 --> 00:12:57,911
RAJESH: Oh, okay.
Uh, "Brothers and sisters l have none...

219
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:00,554
...but this man's father is my father's son.

220
00:13:00,759 --> 00:13:02,431
Who am I looking at?"

221
00:13:02,639 --> 00:13:04,072
[ZOMBIE YELLS]

222
00:13:04,360 --> 00:13:07,033
Yeah, yeah, we get it. You want brains.
Calm down.

223
00:13:07,240 --> 00:13:10,676
Well, if I don't have a brother,
my father's son is me.

224
00:13:10,879 --> 00:13:14,428
And if I'm this man's father, then he's
my son. The answer's "son."

225
00:13:14,639 --> 00:13:17,107
-Ooh! There's a picture of the sun.
-Bet the key's behind it.

226
00:13:17,319 --> 00:13:19,275
Could be somewhere else.

227
00:13:19,999 --> 00:13:21,068
Oh! Got the key.

228
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:23,953
So that's the key to the door? That's it?

229
00:13:24,160 --> 00:13:26,833
We spent $200 on six minutes of fun?

230
00:13:27,040 --> 00:13:29,600
It's like when we bought
that remote-control helicopter...

231
00:13:29,800 --> 00:13:32,394
...and it just flew away.

232
00:13:33,560 --> 00:13:36,313
Sorry, guys.
I really thought the puzzles would be better.

233
00:13:36,520 --> 00:13:39,557
Well, to be fair,
we do all have advanced degrees.

234
00:13:40,279 --> 00:13:43,077
Remember that before you post on Yelp.

235
00:13:45,840 --> 00:13:49,515
"If you were to die this evening with no
opportunity to communicate with anyone...

236
00:13:49,720 --> 00:13:52,359
...what would you most regret
not having told someone?"

237
00:13:53,360 --> 00:13:56,397
So it would be today? Huh.

238
00:13:57,680 --> 00:14:01,468
Eh, I suppose there's something satisfying
about dying on my birthday.

239
00:14:02,279 --> 00:14:04,747
-Today is your birthday?
-Yes.

240
00:14:04,960 --> 00:14:08,635
Well, that's always been a secret.
Not even Amy knows.

241
00:14:08,840 --> 00:14:09,829
[SIGHS]

242
00:14:09,999 --> 00:14:12,388
Well, I don't enjoy presents...

243
00:14:12,600 --> 00:14:15,876
...and the thought of people jumping out
and yelling, "Surprise!"...

244
00:14:16,080 --> 00:14:21,029
...fills me with more dread than the words
"George Lucas director's cut."

245
00:14:21,600 --> 00:14:23,318
So why'd you finally tell me?

246
00:14:24,519 --> 00:14:28,228
The point of the experiment
is to be completely honest with each other.

247
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:32,795
Well, thank you for sharing it with me.
I won't tell anyone.

248
00:14:33,280 --> 00:14:34,508
Thank you.

249
00:14:34,720 --> 00:14:37,871
That is so funny.
I never would have pegged you for a Pisces.

250
00:14:38,080 --> 00:14:40,719
You're making it difficult
to love you right now.

251
00:14:43,560 --> 00:14:47,109
-Great news. Your bag was returned.
-Oh, thank God.

252
00:14:47,320 --> 00:14:49,709
It's okay. She's here. Ma's here.

253
00:14:49,920 --> 00:14:51,797
Oh, good. Thank you so much.

254
00:14:51,999 --> 00:14:55,674
Ma, I'm sorry I didn't take you to the airport.

255
00:14:55,879 --> 00:14:59,792
I just want you to know that I'll never
forgive myself for being so selfish.

256
00:14:59,999 --> 00:15:06,029
And I promise to keep you close
for the rest of my life.

257
00:15:06,479 --> 00:15:09,471
Oh, no, that thing's gonna end up
in my bedroom.

258
00:15:12,520 --> 00:15:14,351
That's it. We're done with the questions.

259
00:15:14,560 --> 00:15:17,916
All that's left to do is stare
into each other's eyes for four minutes.

260
00:15:18,120 --> 00:15:21,396
Okay. Wait, hang on. Bladder check.

261
00:15:23,240 --> 00:15:25,037
We're good to go.

262
00:15:26,600 --> 00:15:28,238
-You ready?
-Yes.

263
00:15:28,800 --> 00:15:31,189
And begin.

264
00:15:45,120 --> 00:15:47,714
This is kind of creepy.

265
00:15:48,600 --> 00:15:51,910
-We're not supposed to talk during this part.
-Sorry.

266
00:15:58,120 --> 00:16:00,429
This is kind of creepy.

267
00:16:01,200 --> 00:16:03,919
Do you wanna stop?
I know you have trouble with eye contact.

268
00:16:04,120 --> 00:16:08,875
Well, you have a brown fleck
in your right iris...

269
00:16:09,079 --> 00:16:11,877
...that looks like a Formula One race car...

270
00:16:12,960 --> 00:16:16,316
...so I'm just concentrating on that.

271
00:16:17,280 --> 00:16:20,033
Plus, it's easier around people
that I'm comfortable with.

272
00:16:20,560 --> 00:16:23,597
Aww. Sweetie, I'm comfortable
around you too.

273
00:16:23,800 --> 00:16:26,075
Of course you are. I'm warm and soothing.

274
00:16:28,040 --> 00:16:30,600
I'm like a human bowl of tomato soup.

275
00:16:31,999 --> 00:16:33,557
I meant more like a little brother.

276
00:16:33,879 --> 00:16:34,914
Oh.

277
00:16:36,120 --> 00:16:38,270
Well, I suppose I do think of you as a sister.

278
00:16:40,240 --> 00:16:42,674
And sometimes a mother.

279
00:16:43,359 --> 00:16:45,554
It's getting creepy again.

280
00:16:52,800 --> 00:16:54,074
What?

281
00:16:54,279 --> 00:16:56,839
Just thinking about the day
I met you and Leonard.

282
00:16:57,040 --> 00:17:01,591
It was a Monday afternoon.
You joined us for Indian food.

283
00:17:01,800 --> 00:17:03,916
Can you believe it's been eight years?

284
00:17:04,120 --> 00:17:06,714
And you're still eating our food.

285
00:17:10,159 --> 00:17:14,072
I can't remember a time
you guys weren't in my life.

286
00:17:14,799 --> 00:17:16,517
I remember it perfectly...

287
00:17:17,880 --> 00:17:20,474
...butl have an eidetic memory.

288
00:17:20,680 --> 00:17:25,196
If you're interested, I also remember
how much you owe us for the food.

289
00:17:28,080 --> 00:17:29,752
[TIMER CHIMES]

290
00:17:29,919 --> 00:17:33,594
-That's it. That wasn't so bad.
-No, it wasn't.

291
00:17:34,039 --> 00:17:38,078
Uh, now let's tabulate the results
of the experiment.

292
00:17:38,279 --> 00:17:41,874
I think it's safe to say
that you're not in love with me...

293
00:17:42,079 --> 00:17:43,751
...and I'm not in love with you...

294
00:17:43,959 --> 00:17:49,955
...and psychology has once again
proved itself the doofus of the sciences.

295
00:17:51,199 --> 00:17:54,350
Well, maybe, but I'm still glad we did it.

296
00:17:54,559 --> 00:17:56,550
I do feel closer to you.

297
00:17:57,839 --> 00:17:58,954
And I you.

298
00:17:59,599 --> 00:18:02,238
And yes, that's how you say that.

299
00:18:04,599 --> 00:18:07,477
So given our newfound intimacy...

300
00:18:07,679 --> 00:18:10,193
...l'd say we have some hard choices
to make.

301
00:18:10,400 --> 00:18:13,710
-Like what?
-Gary Con: Do we fly or drive?

302
00:18:14,719 --> 00:18:16,357
Do we wear costumes?

303
00:18:16,560 --> 00:18:20,678
And if so, who gets to be Gary?

304
00:18:25,480 --> 00:18:27,357
Thank you for walking me home.

305
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:30,199
I just wanna make sure you get there safe.

306
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:34,478
Well, this is me.

307
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,151
-lt's been a very interesting evening.
-It really has.

308
00:18:42,319 --> 00:18:43,672
-Surprise!
-Aaaah!

309
00:18:46,880 --> 00:18:49,599
And after I let you be Gary.

310
00:19:15,360 --> 00:19:17,351
[English - us - an]

